The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Magma to raise Rs 36 crore

 A STAFF REPORTER

 Chamria: On growth path

 Calcutta, June 27: The board of Magma Leasing Limited has decided to allot 38 lakh shares on a preferential basis to foreign institutional investors (FIIs), domestic financial institutions (FIs) and high net worth private investors.

 Subject to shareholders approval, the board has proposed to issue shares of Rs 10 each at a premium of Rs 86 aggregating Rs 36.50 crore according to the Securities and Exchange Board of India (Disclosure and Investor Protection) Guidelines 2000 on preferential issue.

 The company had received letters of intent from the respective investors subsequent to which the board agreed to make the allotment. It has convened an extraordinary general meeting on July 21 to obtain the shareholders approval to the proposal. As on date, the promoters of Magma Leasing, Mayank Poddar and Sanjay Chamria, jointly hold a 75.90 per cent stake in the total shareholding, which will come down to 56.89 per cent post allotment.

 Magma Leasing managing director Sanjay Chamria said: The consistent performance by the company has been the key factor in attracting this new investment and investors are upbeat about its future prospects. This would further strengthen Magmas capital resources and help the company fulfil its growth projections for the current year. We are committed to making Magma a market leader by 2007. 

 The Calcutta-based auto and construction equipment financing and leasing company has financed assets worth Rs 1,759.25 crore in 2004-05 and reported a 24.7 per cent rise in after tax profit at Rs 20.36 crore compared with Rs 16.33 crore in the previous fiscal. Its loan disbursement grew 58 per cent to Rs 1,371 crore against Rs 867 crore in the year-earlier. 

 Buoyed by this improved results, the company has set a higher disbursal target at Rs 2,100 crore for the current fiscal. 

 Having operations in 15 states with 56 branches, Magma Leasing also aims to grow at a pace of 50 per cent year-on-year to become the countrys largest non-banking finance and leasing company by 2007.




